        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Restaurant Fire Safety Requirements in San Diego, CA: What Every Operator Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">San Diego's Gaslamp Quarter, Little Italy, North Park, and the growing Barrio Logan restaurant scene make it one of California's most active restaurant fire safety compliance markets. San Diego Fire-Rescue enforces California Fire Code requirements including semi-annual NFPA 96 kitchen suppression inspections. Here's what every San Diego restaurant operator needs to know.</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">NFPA 96 Kitchen Suppression Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">All commercial cooking operations in San Diego producing grease-laden vapors must install and maintain an automatic wet chemical fire suppression system under NFPA 96. This applies to restaurants, bars with food service, hotel kitchens, and corporate cafeterias. San Diego's restaurant compliance spans the dense Gaslamp Quarter entertainment zone, Little Italy's restaurant row, the North Park craft beer and dining district, Mission Valley's restaurant corridor, and coastal dining in Pacific Beach and Ocean Beach. California's OSFM licensing requirement means only state-licensed fire protection contractors can perform compliant kitchen suppression inspections.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Semi-Annual Inspection Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 96 requires kitchen suppression systems to be inspected and serviced semi-annually — twice per year — by a licensed contractor. Records must be maintained on-site and available for San Diego Fire-Rescue Department inspection. Semi-annual means every six months from the last inspection date, not twice per calendar year.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Hood Cleaning Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 96 requires hood cleaning at intervals based on cooking volume: quarterly for high-volume operations (solid fuel cooking, charbroiling, wok cooking, high-volume fryers), semi-annually for moderate volume, annually for low-volume like pizza ovens. Hood cleaning records must be maintained on-site.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Class K Fire Extinguisher</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">A Class K extinguisher must be within 30 feet of all cooking surfaces producing grease-laden vapors. Class K units are specifically designed for cooking oil fires — standard ABC dry chemical is not an adequate substitute. Class K units require annual inspection alongside other extinguishers.</p>
